6 ounce Asparagus
1 unit Shallot
1 unit Lemon
4 ounce Grape Tomatoes
9 ounce Fresh Tomato Ricotta Ravioli
4 ounce Cream Sauce Base
1 teaspoon Garlic Powder
20 g Basil Paste
5 ounce Spinach
1 unit Ciabatta Roll
2 tablespoon Garlic Herb Butter
3 tablespoon Parmesan Cheese
1 tablespoon Cooking Oil
Salt
Pepper

• Bring a medium pot of water to a
boil. (TIP: Cover pot with lid to bring
water to a boil more quickly.) Wash
and dry produce.
• Trim asparagus; cut on a diagonal
into 1-inch pieces. Thinly slice
shallot. Quarter lemon.
• Heat a large drizzle of oil in a hot
large pan. Add asparagus and
tomatoes; season with salt and
pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until asparagus is browned and tomatoes are
blistered, 2-3 minutes. Turn off heat; transfer to a plate. Wipe out pan.

• Once water is boiling, gently add
ravioli to pot. (TIP: Move on to the
next step if the water has not boiled
yet.) Reduce to a low simmer. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until al dente and
floating to the top, 3-4 minutes.
• Reserve ¾ cup pasta cooking water,
then drain. TIP: Gently shake strainer
with ravioli in it to remove as much
moisture as possible.

• While ravioli cooks, heat a drizzle of
oil in pan used for veggies over
medium heat. Add shallot and cook,
stirring constantly, until softened,
30-60 seconds.
• Whisk in cream sauce base, garlic
powder, basil paste, and ¼ cup
plain water (½ cup for 4). Bring
sauce to a boil then add spinach
(in batches if necessary) and stir to
wilt, 30 to 60 seconds. (Spinach may add moisture to your sauce. Cook longer if
you like a thicker sauce!)
• Add drained ravioli, blistered tomatoes and asparagus, and a squeeze of lemon;
toss until evenly coated in a creamy sauce. (If sauce is too thick, add reserved
pasta cooking water 1 TBSP at a time until desired consistency is reached.)
Season with salt and pepper.

• Halve ciabatta and toast. Spread
cut sides with as much garlic
herb butter as you like; halve on a
diagonal.
• Top ravioli with cheese. Serve with
garlic bread and any remaining
lemon wedges on the side.